     2.0 Unix i/o system


          This section gives an overview of the workings of  the  Unix  i/o
          system.    Particular  attention  is  given  to  the  design  and
          implementation of the device driver required  for  interfacing  a
          network node to Unix.

          Unix is a general purpose multi-user interactive  environment  on
          the PDP-11.  It offers a number of features, including

          1.  An  hierarchical  file   system   incorporating   demountable
              volumes,

          2.  Compatible file, device and inter-process I/O,

          3.  The ability to initiate asynchronous processes,

          4.  System command language selectable on a per-user basis,

          5.  Over 100 subsystems including a dozen languages,

          6.  High degree of portability.


          Of particular importance to this document, are points  1  through
          3.   The  Unix  kernel  can  be  considered  as  primarily an I/O
          multiplexor rather than an operating system.   All  system  calls
          implement  some  I/O  primitive,  other  calls are handled by the
          creation of a dedicated asynchronous process in  user  space,  to
          handle  the  function.   This  extends  to  incorporate the basic
          command interpretation functions.  In this way it is possible  to
          define  alternate  command interpretation processes on a per-user
          basis.

          System calls all  present  a  uniform  interface  to  the  kernel
          irregardless  of  which  device  is being addressed.  A device or
          file or inter-process "pipe" is given a filename which  is  based
          upon  an  hierarchical structure or file system.  The form of the
          filename is the path that must be traced in accessing the "file".
          Each  element  of  the  path  is  a filename and each filename is
          separated from it's successor by a  slash  "/".   A  slash  alone
          refers to the root directory file.  (A directory file consists of
          a list of filenames and their appropriate pointer into the system
          file list or "inode list".  The filename /alpha/beta/gamma refers
          to the file gamma existing as an entry in directory  beta,  which
          exists  as  an entry in directory alpha, which exists as an entry
          in the root ("/") directory.)

          To efface the difference between a device and a file existing  on
          the  file  system  volume(s),  the  notion  of "special" files is
          provided.  These files exist as  directory  entries  in  /dev/...
          These special files correspond to the hardware devices that exist
          in the system and to access these devices, it is  necessary  only
