          to     open     the     respective     special     file.     E.g.
          open("/dev/console",...) will cause I/O to be  performed  on  the
          system console.


          2.1 Device classes


               Two device classes are implemented in the Unix  i/o  system;
               block  and  character.   The block interface is suitable for
               devices such as disks, tapes etc, which can be made to  work
               in  512  byte  blocks  and  can  be  used in a direct access
               fashion.   Character-type   devices   have   a   much   more
               straightforward  interface,  although  more work is done and
               time spent, by the driver.

               Devices of both types are named  by  a  major  and  a  minor
               number.  The major number usually selects the driver and the
               minor number selects a  socket  controlled  by  the  driver.
               Both  block  and  character  devices share the same range of
               major numbers.  The overlap is of no  significance  as  both
               sets  of  minor  numbers  are  used as indices into separate
               tables.


          2.2 I/o overview


               When a user process issues an open or a creat  system  call,
               an  entry  is  made  in the per-process data area "u" in the
               table u_ofile.  This table is indexed by the file descriptor
               returned  by  the  system  and  is  used by subsequent read,
               write, status and close system calls.   The  only  entry  in
               u_ofile  is  a pointer into the per-system file table.  This
               table is maintained to map accesses to a  common  file  from
               processes  generated by fork execution.  Thus all entries in
               this table correspond exactly to  each  successful  open  or
               creat  system  call.   The  table entry pointed to, contains
               file access status bits, a count which determines  when  the
               entry  should  be flushed from the table (when all accessing
               processes have closed it.

               There is  also  a  32  bit  file  offset  pointer  used  for
               subsequent  read  or  write  operations.  Finally there is a
               pointer to another per-system table;  the  i-node  table  or
               table of file system node indices.  Each entry in this table
               corresponds to an accessed file.  This entry  describes  the
               context and characteristics of the file existing either as a
               file on a mountable file system or a device special file.

               The major and minor numbers mentioned before  are  retreived
               using this entry in the inode table.  In the case of a block
               device file , the file-system daemon is  invoked  to  return
               the major number corresponding to the device the file exists
   Unix / Dynasty Interface     Jul-24-1980                          Page 4
    Unix i/o system


               on, and the minor number as the node on the device at  which
               the file appears.  With character type special device files,
               the first  word  of  the  file  block  location  vector,  is
               interpreted  as  a  word  containing the major number in the
               high byte and the minor number in the low byte.   The  major
               number  is  used  to  determine  which device, and the minor
               number (usually) is used by the device service routine, as a
               logical socket on the device.

               A user process open or creat request  will  eventually  call
               the  appropriate  device at its open routine, to perform any
               device specific operations (eg.  rewind a tape, turn on  dtr
               lead of a modem).  However, the device close routine is only
               called when the last process closes the file, ie.  when  the
               i-node table entry is being deallocated.

               When a user file access request is initiated, the file table
               entry  and  the  user's  arguments  are used to define three
               variables in the user's address space.  These are  u.u_base,
               u.u_count  and  u.u_offset.  If the file is a character-type
               special device, the appropriate  device  access  routine  is
               called;    it  is  responsible  for  transferring  data  and
               updating the count and current location  appropriately.   If
               not, the file system process is activated to map the logical
               request into the physical file system structures.

               Files can be opened in one of three modes, these are:- READ,
               WRITE and UPDATE.


          2.3 Character device drivers


               The cdevsw system table specifies the interface routines for
               all character devices.  Each device specifies five routines:
               open, close, read, write and special function.

               The open routine is called whenever the file is opened  with
               the  full device number as argument.  The second argument is
               non-zero only if the file is to be written on.

               The close routine is called when the file is called for  the
               last  time.   The  device number is passed as argument.  The
               second argument is non-zero if the last process that  closed
               the file had it open for writing.

               When write is called,  the  device  number  is  supplied  as
               argument.   The  user  buffer  is  accessed and its contents
               copied (usually) a character at a time, to the device  until
               u.u_count  goes  to zero, or the routine cpass() returns -1;
               an  error  condition.   The  routine  iomove  (local_buffer,
               offset,  count,  flag) can be called to move many characters
               at a faster rate, if this is required.
