               The read routine is  called  similarly  to  write  except  a
               return is not made until u.u_count characters have been read
               using either passc (character) or iomove.

               In the case of tty devices, the special function system call
               is  implemented  by the directives stty and gtty (or ioctl).
               The former to set device dependent parameters and the latter
               to interrogate the existing parameters.

               Communication between a device driver's  interrupt  routines
               and  the "top-half" system interface is maintained by queues
               of characters and state variables accessed by both levels.


          2.4 Terminal handling


               The last action of the Unix bootstrap procedure is to create
               a  process  whose  sole  purpose  is  to  execute  the  file
               /etc/init.  The process "init" that  is  created  opens  the
               /dev/console  device and forks a login process for it.  When
               a user has logged in on the console, a  command  interpreter
               process  is forked and the user can access any of the system
               utilities available to him.  To terminate this "single-user"
               mode,  a  control-D  (ascii  EOT)  is  typed.   This  causes
               termination of  the  command  interpreter  (shell)  process.
               Control is then returned to the main line of init which then
               opens and reads the file /etc/ttys and forks  several  times
               to  create  a  process  for  each tty specified in the file.
               Each of  these  processes  opens  the  appropriate  tty  for
               reading  and  writing.  Normally, opening the tty involves a
               delay,  since  the  open  is  not  completed  until  someone
               connects  the  tty  with  the appropriate device driver, and
               initiates communication.  Once the circuit out to the tty is
               established,  the login prompt is written out to the device.
               Characters typed by the tty are read one at a time until  an
               end  of  line sequence is detected.  Initially this input is
               read by the function "getty"  called  from  the  appropriate
               "init"  process.   This function uses the initial input as a
               username/password  combination.   The  file  /etc/passwd  is
               scanned  and  the  input  verified.   If  incorrect,  "init"
               terminates with  an  error  status  and  the  initialization
               sequence  is  restarted  for that tty.  If verified however,
               the file name specified in the command interpreter  slot  of
               the  password  file entry is executed.  Usually this program
               will be the default "shell".  When the shell is executed,  a
               prompt  is  sent  to  the  tty and the shell goes into input
               wait.

               Ultimately the shell will terminate because of an explicitly
               typed  EOT  or  as  a result of hanging up.  A hangup signal
               (#1) is generated and is trapped  by  the  "init"  process's
               main path.  Init interprets a hangup signal to mean the file
               /etc/ttys  should  be  read  again  and  the  initialization
   Unix / Dynasty Interface     Jul-24-1980                          Page 6
    Unix i/o system


               procedure restarted for all terminals affected by the signal
               and also for any  other  ttys  that  have  no  active  shell
               process  executing  for  them.  In this way editing the file
               /etc/ttys to include extra or remove  tty  entries,  can  be
               used  with  a  user  generated hangup signal, to add or drop
               lines without rebooting the system.

               The file /etc/ttys contains an entry for  each  tty  in  the
               configuration.   Each  entry  is  on  a  separate  line  and
               consists of three parameters.  The first parameter is either
               "0"  or  "1",  the  former causes the line (and entry) to be
               ignored by "init", the latter causes  it  to  be  effective.
               The  second  parameter  is  passed  as an argument when init
               calls the function "getty" and specifies action to be  taken
               by   getty   when   activating  the  tty.   E.g.   baud-rate
               recognition,  reading  the  login  name  etc.    The   third
               parameter  is a string which defines the device name for the
               applicable tty.  This string  corresponds  to  the  filename
               entry located in /dev, e.g.  /dev/"tty10".


          2.5 Terminal characteristics


               The special functions entry point into  a  character  device
               driver  (sgtty)  is  used to specify or interrogate a set of
               parameters used  by  the  driver  in  processing  i/o.   The
               parameters of standard tty devices are as follows:-



               1.  a byte specifying the input speed

               2.  a byte specifying the output speed

               3.  a byte containing the character erase character (usually
                   "#")

               4.  a byte containing the  line  delete  character  (usually
                   "@")

               5.  a word specifying a mask of applicable modes as follows


                   1.  000001 - Automatic flow control(XON / XOFF)

                   2.  000002 - Return each character as typed

                   3.  000004 - map upper case to lower case on input

                   4.  000010 - echo all input (full duplex)
   Unix / Dynasty Interface     Jul-24-1980                          Page 7
    Unix i/o system


                   5.  000020 - map CR into LF;  echo CR or LF as CR-LF

                   6.  000040 - raw mode;  wake up  on  all  characters  (8
                       bit)

                   7.  000100 - ority allowed on input

                   8.  000200 - even parity allowed on input

                   9.  001400 - select  1  of  4  algorithms  for  new-line
                       delays

                  10.  006000 - select 1 of 4 algorithms for tab delays

                  11.  030000 - select 1 of 4 algorithms for CR delays

                  12.  040000 - select 1 of 2  algorithms  for  FF  and  VT
                       delays

                  13.  100000 - select 1 of 2 algorithms for BS delays (not
                       implemented)

                  14.  177400 - Delay algorithm selection (all delay)


               6.  Set or clear 'exclusive-use' mode

               7.  Release (hangup) on final close

               8.  Flush input and output buffers



                                      NOTE

         Three special characters are  recognised  by  the  tty  device
         driver  on  input;  the End-of-file character control-D (EOT),
         the process interrupt character (DEL) and the  quit  character
         (FS).    These  characters  usually  produce  special  effects
         involving the processes that  currently  belong  in  the  same
         context  group  defined  by  the tty line on input.  EOT input
         will be recognised by any process reading on the tty line,  as
         an End-of-file indication.  DEL will usually cause any process
         within a context group to terminate (unless prior arrangements
         have  been  made  to field these interrupts).  FS has the same
         effect as DEL  except  that  any  terminated  process  in  the
         context  group  will  have a core image file created from it's
         in-core text and data segments.


