     3.0 Unix / Network Interface


          This section describes the way in  which  the  network  interface
          will be implemented so as to make use of the general i/o handling
          characteristics of both Unix and the network node code.


          3.1 Hardware


               The tty driver code in Unix currently supports  only  a  few
               low  speed  asynchronous  lines  to  which  terminals can be
               interfaced, viz the KL/DL11, DH11 and DC11.   As  a  way  of
               interfacing  two PDP11 systems, two back to back DR11c's (or
               DRV11's) can be configured such that output on  one  implies
               input  on the other and vice versa.  Various measurements of
               this inter-bus parallel communication path have  shown  that
               the  rate  of  data transfer is limited by software to about
               10,000 bps, which makes  it  a  good  high  speed  link  for
               multiplexed terminal i/o.

               Unix software will run unchanged on any  PDP-11  having  the
               appropriate  memory mapping hardware (e.g.  an 11/34, 11/40,
               11/23,  11/45,  11/60,  11/70).   Note  that  separation  of
               Instruction  and  Data space using active page registers, is
               only  available  on  the  11/45  and  up.   Thus  on   these
               processors,  a user process can be a maximum of 64K words in
               length.  Whereas on the others, a process is constrained  to
               32K words.

               The Dynasty hardware configuration  consists  of  a  Dynasty
               cabinet containing an 8 slot, Q-bus backplane with 30 active
               bus sockets.  The processor used is an LSI-11/23 with memory
               management  but  without floating point.  Memory consists of
               between 96K-128K words of MOS memory.  Eight local terminals
               can  be supported (of which one is the device /dev/console),
               by two dual height DLV11Js each having 4  SLUs  and  limited
               modem  control.   Network interfacing is implemented using a
               dual height DRV11.  Online mass storage is supplied with the
               'Universal Controller' which controls a 26Mb Winchester disk
               plus up too 2 RX02/IBM double density floppies.

               Network node software runs on an LSI-11/2.  Normal  terminal
               interfaces  on  the  local  network  are DLV11's or DZV11's.
               Network interfaces to Tymnet are in  the  form  of  multiple
               logical  "tty"  circuits  over  a DUV11 synchronous protocol
               line.  Daisy-chained nodes are connected via DRV11  parallel
               interfaces or over a serial DUV11 line.  Host interfacing is
               via DRV11.
