          3.2 Software


               The concept of having a dynamic pool  of  character  devices
               with  arbitrary physical connection requirements, is not new
               to Unix.  The connection of dialed up lines to Unix maps  in
               identically.   Each  physical  line  is  associated  with  a
               special file name and a login process is forked  for  it  by
               init.

               The point at which the  interface  to  the  network  becomes
               orthogonal to the above scheme is when a circuit needs to be
               established from a Unix process to a network  address.   The
               implementation  will  map  special  file  names  of the form
               "/dev/DV", into  logical  ports  implemented  by  the  DRV11
               device driver, where DV indicates the mnemonic for a network
               device as follows:-

                    HS - A local network host
                    TR - A local network terminal
                    WD - A load device on a network node
                    ST - A status device on a network node
                    LP - A line printer device on a network node
                    NT - A TYMNET T.201 gateway on a network node

               In addition to the device name, a local network node or host
               must be specified.  This is accomplished by appending ':nnn'
               to the  filename  (e.g.   "/dev/HS:676"  connects  to  local
               network  host  676).   This will be implemented by modifying
               the pathname decoding logic in  the  kernel  such  that  the
               string 'DV:nnn' is passed to the driver's open routine entry
               point.  The node / host interface protocol is then  employed
               to  establish  the  outgoing  connection  within  the  local
               network.  If multiple DRV11 interfaces exist, then each will
               be  tried  in turn until either a connect ack is returned or
               either a connect nak  other  than  'device  unavailable'  is
               returned, or the DRV11 list is exhausted.

               If only the local network destination node or host number is
               specified  with  the  device name, then the 'wild' socket is
               connected to at the destination (i.e.  the  first  available
               socket  on  the  device specified).  If a specific socket is
               required, then ';mmm' is  appended  to  the  filename  (e.g.
               "/dev/lp:670;2"  connects  to  line printer number 2 on node
               670).

               Incoming connections from the  network,  will  have  a  port
               number  assigned from a dynamic pool of available sockets on
               the applicable DRV11 interface.  These sockets are  assigned
               from  n(max)  down.  Outgoing connections will have a socket
               allocated from  n(min)  up.   The  interface  is  considered
               exhausted if they meet in the middle.
   Unix / Dynasty Interface     Jul-24-1980                         Page 10
    Unix / Network Interface


               When attempting an outgoing connection,  the  local  network
               requires  a connect privilege level.  The device driver will
               assign this value based  upon  who  the  user  is.   If  the
               super-user,  then  the  maximum  of 377(8) is assigned, else
               177(8).

               The host device  when  connected  to  will  be  an  incoming
               connection  request on the apropriate local network host and
               must therefore go through the applicable login sequence  via
               subsequent IO calls to the driver.

               The terminal device when connected to will allow  a  process
               to  drive  a  terminal device.  Nodes are usually configured
               such that the minimum connect privilege is 200 octal.   Thus
               only the super-user can do this.

               The load  device  when  connected  to,  will  allow  a  host
               adjacent or a node adjacent node on the local network, to be
               down-line loaded from the user process.  An  error  response
               is  generated  if  the  node specified does not exist on the
               network or the node is already loaded or is  not  processing
               it's  bootstrap.   The  load  device  for  a  node  directly
               connected to the host, is resident in the device driver  and
               thus  no  network  dialogue  is necessary.  However the node
               bootstrap protocol must be included in the device driver.

               The status device when connected to will allow a  dialog  to
               be  initiated  between  the user process and the appropriate
               software device in the node via subsequent IO calls.

               The line printer device when connected to will allow text to
               be spooled out to it from the user process.

               The TYMNET gateway device when connected to  will  create  a
               circuit  to  the TYMNET supervisor via the gateway indicated
               by 'nnn' (the local network node number).  The login  string
               is  then  written  to  the  NT  device in node 'nnn' and the
               circuit into TYMNET established.
