          3.3 Protocols


               This section describes the data flow that will be handled by
               the  DRV11  device  driver  in  the  Unix host.  It deals in
               multiplexed  circuits   through   the   DRV11   to   various
               destinations in the local (and remote) network.

               3.3.1 Node loading

                    When Unix  is  first  brought  up,  the  state  of  the
                    adjacent network node ('base') is not known.  Thus when
                    the first open call causes entry  into  the  driver,  a
                    startup  handshake protocol is observed.  This involves
                    sending a reset message to the base and timing  out  on
                    the  response.   Until  an  acknowledge to the reset is
                    received, the base is considered  down.   All  outgoing
                    connection  requests  will be rejected with 'link down'
                    errors, except the open  of  "/dev/wd:nnn"  (where  nnn
                    refers  to  the  base).   At  this  point,  the startup
                    handshake protocol is suspended and the  load  protocol
                    established.   This  is  accomplished  by  reseting the
                    interface with the following message.

                         Byte     Content     Meaning
                         ----     -------     -------
                          0-1     002307      Prefix
                          2-3     177777      Node bootstrap reset
                          4-5          0      Message data checksum

                    The base is then timed out on a response for 5 seconds.
                    If  the  timeout  elapses,  the  open  is  rejected  as
                    'time-out' (no reply).  If a response is received which
                    is  not  either  100307  or  100707,  then  the open is
                    rejected  with  'inconsistent  link  data'.    If   the
                    response  is  either of 100307 or 100707 (message ack),
                    then the open is returned successful.

                    Once the open has returned successful, the user process
                    can  load data by writing it to the file.  If any error
                    is encountered in loading, then all future writes, will
                    be  returned  with  an  error value (the nak received =
                    140307 or 140707).  (It is recommended that  load  data
                    be  written in 128 byte blocks, so that an error can be
                    related to a specific write).   The  driver  sends  the
                    data  written  through  the  interface in the following
                    format.

                         Byte     Content     Meaning
                         ----     -------     -------
                          0-1     002307      Prefix
                          2-3        128      Message data bytecount
                          4-131        -      Message data
                        132-133        -      Message data checksum (4-131)
   Unix / Dynasty Interface     Jul-24-1980                         Page 12
    Unix / Network Interface


                    All data is sent in an 8 bit wide mode and the open  of
                    "/dev/wd" is done in exclusive use mode, by default.

                    When all data has been transferred,  the  user  process
                    closes the file.  This causes entry to be made into the
                    driver close routine.  The driver takes  this  to  mean
                    that  the  base  should be told to enter it's secondary
                    bootstrap (just loaded).  This is accomplished  by  the
                    message:-

                         Byte     Content     Meaning
                         ----     -------     -------
                          0-1     002307      Prefix
                          2-3          0      boot
                          4-5          0      message data checksum

                    The  driver  then  re-enters  it's  startup   handshake
                    protocol.   Eventually  the driver will receive a reset
                    from the base or a reset  ack  to  it's  own  initiated
                    reset.   The  base  will  then  be  marked  as  up  and
                    connections allowed.

                    Down line loading of a remote node (not adjacent to the
                    host)  works  in  a similar fashion at the user process
                    level, with the exception  that  a  6  character,  left
                    justified  and null padded node number, must be written
                    before the load image.  This number is the network node
                    number of the node to be loaded.  /dev/wd:nnn refers to
                    the load device in a node which  is  adjacent  to  this
                    node  number.   Thus  "cat  idmmm  svnnn > /dev/wd:mmm"
                    loads a remote network node where 'nnn' and  'mmm'  are
                    different.

                    The load sequence  at  the  driver  level  is  however,
                    totally  different.   If there are no network links up,
                    the open is refused with 'link down'.  If  the  circuit
                    cannot be built on any of the available links, the open
                    is refused with  the  first  device  specific  or  last
                    non-device  specific, error message.  If the circuit is
                    built successfully then the open is successful and  the
                    6  char node number to load is written, followed by the
                    load data.

                    There is a range of values that can be returned on  the
                    circuit from the destination load device, these are.

                         Code     Value(8)  Meaning
                         ----     -----     -------
                         LROK      100      Node to load connected
                         LRINN     101      Illegal node number
                         LRNSN     102      No such node
                         LRNNI     103      Node not idle
                         LRCSE     104      Checksum error
                         LRPOV     105      Packet overflow
   Unix / Dynasty Interface     Jul-24-1980                         Page 13
    Unix / Network Interface


                         LRPCE     106      Protocol error
                         LRFIN     107      Node booted successfully
                         LRTIM     110      Node bootstrap timed out
                         LRRFS     111      Refused by load device
                         LRNHW     112      No hardware present

                    The driver will return the  appropriate  negated  value
                    (with  the  exception  of  LROK and LRFIN which it will
                    simply ignore) upon receipt.  Thus a write  can  return
                    the error code for a preceding write.

                    Again, on the file close, the boot message will be sent
                    on  the  circuit.   The close will not return until the
                    LRFIN, an error or a response has  been  timed  out  (5
                    secs) or been received.
