          3.4 Implementation


               This section describes the implementation  strategy  of  the
               interface between the network and Unix.

               3.4.1 User level


                    When Unix comes up, it comes up  in  single-user  mode.
                    The  user  at the system console decides when multiuser
                    is to be initiated and types  in  a  control  D.   When
                    multiuser  comes  up,  the process init opens /etc/ttys
                    and forks an instance of getty for each  enabled  entry
                    in that file (they correspond to "/dev/ttyX" files).

                    To  invoke  the  network  interface,   "cat   svnnn   >
                    /dev/wd:nnn", is executed where svnnn is the node nnn's
                    load  image.   Three  situations  are  handled  on  the
                    completion  of the output file open.  Firstly, the node
                    is  executing  it's  bootstrap  and  requires  downline
                    loading.   Secondly,  the  node  is  dead and cannot be
                    loaded and thirdly the node  is  up  and  communicating
                    with the host.  In both the second and third cases, the
                    open is  returned  unsuccessful.   In  the  first  case
                    however,  the  input  file  is  opened  and  written to
                    /dev/wd':nnn' until EOF.

                    Incoming connections from network ttys,  will  cause  a
                    previous  open  of  a  /dev/ttyX file, to be completed.
                    The instantiation of init will then call getty with the
                    appropriate  character from the /etc/ttys entry.  Getty
                    will use the character to determine  the  login  string
                    format  it will receive.  In particular, a modification
                    to getty is necessary to  change  the  TYMNET  supplied
                    login  message  into  the  appropriate  Unix  character
                    sequence, before login is invoked.   The  DRV11  driver
                    will  greatly  facilitate  this by propagating only the
                    username and the password.
